text:
in discussion with @zoomtv about abuse of power, and what it means. why women donтАЩt speak up, and why we as a society judge women for doing what they do, even though we do not judge the men abusing their power. ask yourself how often you look at a new actress and say тАШshe mustтАЩve fucked her way on topтАЩ, but at the same time, we donтАЩt look at the men that are casting them and say тАШi wonder how often he has abused his power to misuse girls.тАЩ she does it even though she shouldnтАЩt have to, and you slut shame her. 
he does it, and you say тАШso many sluts are ready to give inтАЩ
really?
the same logic applies when we talk about physical or sexual abuse towards women all over our society. we judge the victim, we dissect her character, we refuse to believe her story. 
for those that are still confused, #metoo is about work place assault, it is also about psychical and sexual abuse in relationships. me too is about a womanтАЩs right to be treated equally. the campaign started by people in media to bring sexism in the industry to lime light - but that doesnтАЩt mean its limited to work places. 
please stop asking women to тАШlimitтАЩ their assault stories to one space, as though if sheтАЩs been raped or beaten at home, itтАЩs no longer me too. thatтАЩs the worst thing you could to do a movement this large and sensitive, tell women their stories of abuse are not important.
me too, is about empowering women. all women, everywhere.
me too, is about empowering women.

text:
milkman review: the pleasure derived from this book is akin to a strenuous round of exercise тАФ you will feel exerted, tired, spent, tinged with an endorphin-induced afterglow. 
_
the setting: a community in northern ireland during the time of the troubles тАФ тАЬknife-edged times, primal times, with everybody suspicious of everybodyтАЭ. people are divided between тАЬrenouncersтАЭ versus тАЬdefendersтАЭ тАФ тАЬthis side of the roadтАЭ versus тАЬthat side of the roadтАЭ тАФ subjected to bomb scares, hijackings, paramilitary rule, kangaroo courts, surveillance, and endless cycles of revenge and counter-revenge. unwritten rules of allegiance dictate the names you give your children, the television programs you are permitted to watch, the brands of food you eat, the shops you frequent, the hymns you sing, the bus stop you use:
_
тАЬthere was the fact that you created a political statement everywhere you went, and with everything you did, even if you didnтАЩt want to.тАЭ
_
naturally, such an intense climate of tribalism and communal self-policing leaves very little room for individual expression.
_
enter our narrator, a young irish woman living on the renouncer side of the community. she is seen as an outcast, declared тАЬbeyond-the-paleтАЭ, due to her fondness for тАЬreading-while-walkingтАЭ тАФ a deliberate ritual to escape the political mental space by losing herself in 19th century literature. she has nine siblings and a mother who continually harangues her to get married. when a prominent paramilitary figures, dubbed тАЬmilkmanтАЭ, becomes sexually interested in her, his insistent attentions and subtle means of psychological manipulation start to chisel away at her sense of self.
_
onto the language: there is a freedom and plasticity to burnsтАЩ writing that echoes thought. at times, in an intense burst of proustian introspection, the narrative zooms in on a single moment in time, letting it mushroom to fill twenty pages of descriptive text. at other times, the narration is inflected with an austenian tick тАФ a nod to the narratorтАЩs 19th century literary diet тАФ with its fondness for circumlocution. a liar is a тАЬteller of untruthsтАЭ. mad people are тАЬcreatures of another planet...тАЭ
_
(continued in comments ЁЯСЗЁЯП╗)

text:
only 310 of out of every 1,000 sexual assault cases are reported to the authorities. which means that about 2 out of 3 sexual assaults cases arenтАЩt reported. you may be asking yourself, why donтАЩt victims report their assault? this is because victims are silenced. victims are silenced by fear. fear of their abuser, fear of what others will think of them, fear of their personal experience being talked about, fear of the names they will be called and the questions they will be asked. itтАЩs not as easy as just telling a police officer what happened. people question you and ask you things like, тАЬwhy didnтАЩt you try harder to get out of the situation?тАЭ, and they say that they donтАЩt believe you, that the person who abused you would never do something like that. this is the america we live in. where a victim finally finds the courage to speak up and is condemned, judged, and silenced. this has to end. we need to change this world. we need to listen to victims and provide them with love and believe their stories. if you are a victim of sexual assault, i encourage you to speak up about your situation and stand strong. because you are strong. you can get through this and you are not alone. together, we can all unite and empower victims to stand strong with courage. we can believe them and listen to them. we can change this america that we are currently living in, one step at a time. #whyididntreport #metoo #survivors #believesurvivors

.
morgenavond helpen we vanaf 20:30u een nieuw koppel aan hun massief houten keukenfrontjes (op dinsdag en woensdag 23 + 24 oktober). beter kijkt u dus weer naar house rules op net5. zien jullie misschien onze wouter ook nog even! oeh! ЁЯСп
.
keukenfronten dus. we maken ze praktisch voor iedere keuken. in de gewenste groottes; houtsoort; afwerking; greep type; etc. 
keukenbladen van hout of steen zijn eveneens mogelijk. 
en plaatstaal zijn we inmiddels ook erg bedreven in. voor open vakken combinaties of als corpus voor uw keukenkast met houten of fenix deurtjes.
.
goed. dat. en nog enorm veel ander maatwerk en #design voor uw interieur natuurlijk. schitterende meubels; verlichting en woonaccessoires. ЁЯШМ
.

text: donald palmerine witnessed a sexual assault in 1969 and decided earlier this month to tell his story publicly in an essay published by the @washingtonpost earlier this month. palmerine details how he attended a party when he was 17 and witnessed the rape of an unconscious woman. for the next 50 years, he was silent though the guilt stayed with him. when dr. christine blasey-ford testified before the senate judiciary committee, he was compelled to tell this story and encourage men to speak up in the era of the #metoo movement: "i wanted to tell this story because i believe it's time for men to tell the truth about the ways they've abused women and what our role has been in creating a culture that tolerates this"

text:
my fellow female farmer @tara.b.coronado inspired me to share a bit about my mental health journey today in honor of #mentalhealthmonday. ЁЯТХ
i constantly struggle with anxiety. it used to be much much worse. i havenтАЩt suffered a panic attack since 2015. ЁЯТХ
much of my anxiety stems from being assaulted four times during my early 20s and witnessing the death of a child in a horrible accident. because of these experiences, i struggled with intimacy and suffered from what i think was ptsd. i took those experiences and wrote about them in the television show i produced. it was cathartic and helped me heal. ЁЯТХ
i knew that if i hid from these parts of my story, they would find me and eat me alive. i had to face them head on and share them with others in order to accept them as a part of who i am. ЁЯТХ
iтАЩve chosen to see my time in chicago as a huge push from the universe to leave and get to this rural life i feel so blessed to live now. the farm and the animals ground me, quite literally. i feel that my journey has lead me right where i need to be.ЁЯТХ
when anxiety does show up, i breathe through it and focus on the present moment. i remind myself iтАЩm worthy of love. i say to myself i am safe. then i go get a hug from paul. ЁЯТХ
itтАЩs so important to share this type of stuff. i hope in sharing today, you feel less alone in your struggle with anxiety. #wearebettertogether ЁЯТХ
#mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth #anxiety #anxietyhelp #farmlifebestlife #iamcountryside #metoo #survivor #abundancemindset #naturetherapy #farmingtherapy #gardentherapy #farmher #thisiswomenswork

text:
a wounded warrior-
she stumbled on her way,
tripping on her own feet,
her hands bleeding,
her soul still healing,
but all she could see was a battlefield ahead.

fighting her urge to cry,
and leading her steps to the warzone.
she moved ahead,
because she knew only she can win her fights for herself.

her legs were aching,
because she was a victim of his cruelty.
her body was shaking,
because the trauma was too much to realise.

she was still walking towards the war,
she knew she's gonna lose if she isn't strong.
the other warriors looked at her with strange eyes,
they knew something was wrong but what, they couldn't determine.

she walked to a sword,
and picked it with grace,
the pain in her parts,
was making her go insane.

she remembers how he crawled
on her skin.
looking at her like a prey in his den,
he moved forward to hunt for his little game.

with every scream,
she lost her dignity,
tear by tear,
blood by blood.

all he could see
was her innocence,
which he ripped apart from her,
because he was feeling a bit of lust.

she snapped out of her flashbacks,
and picked the sword.
with a scream in her throat,
and rage in her eyes,
she moved ahead killing all those who killed her pride.

for strangers maybe she was a lunatic,
but for those who could see the blood between her legs,
she was a wounded warrior.

text:
meet the arise staff! ЁЯСЛ

alexa perez is our outreach specialist and she has been with us for 1 1/2 years. her favorite part about arise is that they will go to the ends of the earth to help a survivor, they do not give up easily.

when asked what she thought others should know about sexual violence she said: "sexual violence isnтАЩt just some trend on social media, it is so much more than that. sexual violence has been and will be around for a long time. but, we can cut that time short if we stop being fearful of talking about it. we must become more educated on how to not only support survivors but, how to create a world where sexual violence is basically non-existent. in the words of malala yousafzai тАЬwhen the whole world is silent, even one voice becomes powerful.тАЭ #endsexualviolence #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #arisenm

text:
#notallmen , but it's definitely all women. 
have you ever, for no explicable reason, been extra aware about the men around you?

i got a guide on a solo trip and he was truly helpful. he went a little out of his way, translating for me some of the things the locals said, ensuring that i got to my next destination, and such. 
little things. thoughtful things. and then he left. 
it was then that i felt foolish, because in my life when strange men help, there is (usually)  something fishy going on. not always. but self-preservation has evolved with the idea of never taking a chance. 
#womensrights #equalrights

text:
jyot se jyot jagate chalo!
.
.
i have been contemplating writing about this for a long time. is the #metoo movement only about telling our stories? sharing the details of our traumas. i agree that staying silent doesnтАЩt help. but who do you open up to?
.
.
i love #storytelling and to a large extent understand that opening up about a trauma is one of the first steps towards our healing journey. however, to all the survivors who have shared their stories, who are contemplating and who are still not sure about it... i want to say, it doesnтАЩt have to be social media post with a me too hashtag, it doesnтАЩt have to be a open mic performance, you donтАЩt need to open up to strangers if you donтАЩt want to... you can choose to open up to a close friend or family, you can even pen it down in your diary or share it with your pet. to dispel the dark fear from within, you can take smaller steps, light just a small lamp within.
.
.
open up you must. but, you decide which way you feel comfortable and once the pain has been shared, the journey towards healing must begin. connect with communities, therapy and fellow survivors to help you on your resolve to heal yourself.
.
.
having said that, i have great respect for women who come forward to share their stories on public platforms. i acknowledge their hurt! itтАЩs mind-numbing... my blood boils... i relive their horrors and it brings back memories of incidents i faced as a woman. it also gives strength to many who have bottled-up, repressed and silenced their pain. i read these stories not only to know what happened but also to know how they overcame the hurt, how they are healing.
.
.
this movement is larger than sharing stories. we must help ourselves and survivors to get connected to the necessary healing and advocacy resources, along the road shattering our old patriarchal culture. striving to achieve a balanced world!
.
.
#timesupnow #ibelieveher #ibelievesurvivors #metooindia #metoomovement #womenforwomen #notashamed @metoo_in #advocacy #healing #sexualassaultawareness #stopvictimblaming

the issue:
while celebrating the dusshera yesterday,
a tragedy took place and still there is no one to blame.
.
.
1)the organisers knew about the lapse.
but still organised the event just to impress their leader.
.
.
2)mrs.navjot sidhu,who was the chief guest,also knew that it will happen.
but did nothing to avoid the tragedy.
she should have opted out of the event.
but she went and sealed with her visit,
the death of tons of people.
.
.
3)the police gave the clearance to organise.
.
.
4)the railway said the people trespassed their territory.
.
.
5)more than 100 died and more than 300 injured.
but the statistics are hidden due to political pressure.
.
.
6)politics is going on upon the issue.
.
.
7)the people who lost their loved ones still seek answers.
.
.
they say it's people's fault for standing upon the tracks.
but they won't admit that they organised the event at a wrong place which was vulnerable to get congested for their favourite leader was coming herself.
but the leader said that the place had been used for many years and nothing happened back then.
.
.
she meant that she was just unlucky for the incident took place in her presence and not anyone else.
.
.
and navjaat shishu says it's a big tragedy but occurred due to god's will.
he asked not to politicise the issue.
but is he willing to take the responsibility for the sins 
he and his family have committed...???
.
.
well,clap clap clapЁЯСПЁЯСПЁЯСП
.
.
p.s.a man named dalbir singh,
who played ravana that day,
also died in the tragedy.
and mrs.sidhu has nothing to say.
just one thing,
we burn the effigy of the demons every year.
but when do we burn the demons that lurk inside all of us.
.
.
.
